            <span class="who">
                <span class="">Abraham Kimmelmann</span>:
            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="kimmelmannA" start="1321.440" end="x">Yes, fifty. Up to fifty. These had to go to Germany.</span>
        </li>
                <li>
            <span class="who">
                <span class="">David Boder</span>:
            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="boderD" start="1326.579" end="x">They had to go, or they could go?</span>
        </li>
                <li>
            <span class="who">
                <span class="">Abraham Kimmelmann</span>:
            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="kimmelmannA" start="1327.749" end="x">They could, but if they didn't want, they had to. But it wasn't done in a way that they would notify the Jewish Community Council. They didn't send an order to the Kultusgemeinde telling them that they would need so and so many workers for Germany because they were afraid they couldn't trust the Jewish Community Council with such a thing. And so they went through with it themselves and in the following manner. From the early morning, it was about 4:30 they sent to the city a certain number of policemen. And they gave them the Jewish addresses and they simply got us from the beds. I still remember when they came into our house, my father wasn't home at the moment, by accident and fortunately so he was in <a class="placename" href="#vothL98">Sosnowice</a>.</span>
        </li>
                <li>
            <span class="who">
                <span class="">David Boder</span>:
